{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"ff9b397c-c680-4189-84b6-c03b5616b947","content":"**Exit code 8** is MTP's \"no tests discovered\" code. VSTest returned 0 for empty assemblies; MTP treats it as an error by design.\n\nYou have two options — pick whichever fits your CI:\n\n**Option 1 — CLI flag** (preferred, per-command):\n```bash\ndotnet test -- --ignore-exit-code 8\n```\n\n**Option 2 — Environment variable** (applies globally in the pipeline):\n```bash\nexport TESTINGPLATFORM_EXITCODE_IGNORE=8\ndotnet test\n```\n\nBoth tell MTP to treat \"zero tests found\" as success (exit 0), which restores the VSTest behavior for your conditional-compilation assemblies. No code or `.csproj` changes needed.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"e495ab89-6f31-4dcc-82e8-71e886538564","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"Now I understand the issue clearly. The project uses `EnableMSTestRunner` (Microsoft.Testing.Platform), and all tests are behind `#if INCLUDE_SLOW_TESTS`. When that symbol isn't defined, zero tests are discovered, and MTP returns exit code 8 (which means \"no tests found\").\n\nWith VSTest, zero tests discovered was exit code 0. With MTP, it's a non-zero exit code by design — it treats \"no tests found\" as an error to catch misconfiguration.\n\nThe fix is to tell MTP to ignore this exit code. There are a few approaches:\n\n1. **`--ignore-exit-code 8`** on the `dotnet test` command line\n\n\n2. **Environment variable `TESTINGPLATFORM_EXITCODE_IGNORE`** set to `8`\n3. **MSBuild property `TestingPlatformShowTestsFailure`** set to `false` in the `.csproj` to suppress the failure when no tests are found\n\nThe cleanest approaches are the CLI flag `dotnet test -- --ignore-exit-code 8` or the environment variable, but for a project-level solution that avoids CI pipeline changes, there might be an MSBuild property like `TestingPlatformExitProcessOnNoTests` that controls whether the process exits with a non-zero code when no tests run. I'll go with the environment variable approach since it's the cleanest project-level solution, and I can also mention the CLI flag option for CI pipelines.","outputTokens":1040,"requestId":"3403:3675E8:9D50EB:B8073F:69F3FC05"},"id":"788c7730-109e-4b38-b3b7-b4118b94a7ea","timestamp":"2026-05-01T01:04:29.053Z","parentId":"035da607-dd39-4c64-82f6-c6d39cc259bc"}
